# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abiogenesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Comet **81P/Wild**, also known as **Wild 2** (pronounced "vilt two") (/ˈvɪlt/ *VILT*), is a comet with a period of 6.4 years named after Swiss astronomer Paul Wild, who discovered it on January 6, 1978, using a 40-cm Schmidt telescope at Zimmerwald, Switzerland.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] For most of its 4.5 billion-year lifetime, Wild 2 probably had a more distant and circular orbit.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] In September 1974, it passed within 1.0 million km (0.62 million mi) of the planet Jupiter, the strong gravitational pull of which perturbed the comet's orbit and brought it into the inner Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Its orbital period changed from 43 years to about 6 years, and its perihelion is now about 1.59 AU (238 million km).
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Prior to its encounter with Jupiter in 1974, the comet had an orbital period of around 43 years with an aphelion at around 25 AU and a perihelion of just under 5 AU.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] The encounter reduced the aphelion and perihelion to its present value of around 5 and 1.5 AU, respectively.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] NASA's Stardust Mission launched a spacecraft, named *Stardust*, on February 7, 1999.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] It flew by Wild 2 on January 2, 2004, and collected particle samples from the comet's coma, which were returned to Earth along with interstellar dust it collected during the journey.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Seventy-two close-up shots were taken of Wild 2 by *Stardust*.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] They revealed a surface riddled with flat-bottomed depressions, with sheer walls and other features that range from very small to up to 2 km (1.2 mi) across.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] These features are believed to be caused by impact craters or gas vents.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] During *Stardust*'s flyby, at least 10 gas vents were active.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] The comet itself has a diameter of 5 km (3.1 mi).
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] As of 2006, the composition of the dust has contained a wide range of organic compounds, including two that contain biologically usable nitrogen.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Indigenous aliphatic hydrocarbons were found with longer chain lengths than those observed in the diffuse interstellar medium.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] No hydrous silicates or carbonate minerals were detected, which suggests a lack of aqueous processing of Wild 2 dust.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Very few pure carbon (CHON) particles were found in the samples returned.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] A substantial amount of crystalline silicates such as olivine, anorthite and diopside were found, materials only formed at high temperature.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] This is consistent with previous observations of crystalline silicates both in cometary tails and in circumstellar disks at large distances from the star.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] "Both in the Solar System and in circumstellar disks crystalline silicates are found at large distances from the star.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] The origin of these silicates is a matter of debate.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Although in the hot inner-disk regions crystalline silicates can be produced by means of gas-phase condensation or thermal annealing, the typical grain temperatures in the outer-disk (2–20 au) regions are far below the glass temperature of silicates of approx 1,000 K.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] The crystals in these regions may have been transported outward through the disk or in an outward-flowing wind.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] An alternative source of crystalline silicates in the outer disk regions is in situ annealing, for example by shocks or lightning.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] A third way to produce crystalline silicates is the collisional destruction of large parent bodies in which secondary processing has taken place.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Results from a study reported in the September 19, 2008 issue of the journal *Science* has revealed an oxygen isotope signature in the dust that suggests an unexpected mingling of rocky material between the center and edges of the Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Despite the comet's birth in the icy reaches of outer space beyond Pluto, tiny crystals collected from its halo appear to have been forged in the hotter interior, much closer to the Sun.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] In April 2011, scientists from the University of Arizona discovered evidence of the presence of liquid water.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] They found iron and copper sulfide minerals that must have formed in the presence of water.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] The discovery is in conflict with the existing paradigm that comets never get warm enough to melt their icy bulk.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] Either collisions or radiogenic heating might have provided the necessary energy source.
[src:abiogenesis/81p-wild] On August 14, 2014, scientists announced the collection of possible interstellar dust particles from the *Stardust* spacecraft since returning to Earth in 2006.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Bill Bryson wrote this book because he was dissatisfied with his *scientific knowledge*—that was, not much at all.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] He writes that science was a distant, unexplained subject at school.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Textbooks and teachers alike did not ignite the passion for knowledge in him, mainly because they never delved into the *whys*, *hows*, and *whens*.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Bryson describes graphically and in layperson's terms the size of the universe and that of atoms and subatomic particles.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] He then explores the history of geology and biology and traces life from its first appearance to today's modern humans, emphasizing the development of the modern *Homo sapiens*.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Furthermore, he discusses the possibility of the Earth being struck by a meteorite and reflects on human capabilities of spotting a meteor before it impacts the Earth, and the extensive damage that such an event would cause.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] He also describes some of the most recent destructive disasters of volcanic origin in the history of our planet, including Krakatoa and Yellowstone National Park.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] A large part of the book is devoted to relating humorous stories about the scientists behind the research and discoveries and their sometimes eccentric behaviours.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Bryson also speaks about modern scientific views on human effects on the Earth's climate and livelihood of other species, and the magnitude of natural disasters such as earthquakes, volcanoes, tsunamis, hurricanes, and the mass extinctions caused by some of these events.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] An illustrated edition of the book was released in November 2005.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] A few editions in audiobook form are also available, including an abridged version read by the author, and at least three unabridged versions.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Recognising both the errors in the original and, more importantly, the significant advances in scientific knowledge, a second edition was published in late 2025.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] This contains extensive revisions to all chapters.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] The book received generally favourable reviews, with reviewers citing the book as informative, well-written, and entertaining.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] In 2004, this book won Bryson The Aventis Prizes for Science Books for best general science book.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] Bryson later donated the GBP£10,000 prize to the Great Ormond Street Hospital children's charity.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] It was shortlisted for the Samuel Johnson Prize for the same year.
[src:abiogenesis/a-short-history-of-nearly-everything] In 2005, the book won the EU Descartes Prize for science communication.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:abiogenesis/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:abiogenesis/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The **abundance of the chemical elements** is a measure of the occurrences of the chemical elements relative to all other elements in a given environment.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance is measured in one of three ways: by *mass fraction* (in commercial contexts often called *weight fraction*), by *mole fraction* (fraction of atoms by numerical count, or sometimes fraction of molecules in gases), or by *volume fraction*.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Volume fraction is a common abundance measure in mixed gases such as planetary atmospheres, and is similar in value to molecular mole fraction for gas mixtures at relatively low densities and pressures, and ideal gas mixtures.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Most abundance values in this article are given as mass fractions.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of chemical elements in the universe is dominated by the large amounts of hydrogen and helium which were produced during Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to their favorable energetics of formation, described by the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in the Sun and outer planets is similar to that in the universe.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to solar heating, the elements of Earth and the inner rocky planets of the Solar System have undergone an additional depletion of volatile hydrogen, helium, neon, nitrogen, and carbon (which volatilizes as methane).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The crust, mantle, and core of the Earth show evidence of chemical segregation plus some sequestration by density.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lighter silicates of aluminium are found in the crust, with more magnesium silicate in the mantle, while metallic iron and nickel compose the core.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of elements in specialized environments, such as atmospheres, oceans, or the human body, are primarily a product of chemical interactions with the medium in which they reside.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance of each element is expressed as a relative number.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Astronomy uses a logarithmic scale for abundance $\epsilon _{X}$ of element X relative to hydrogen, defined by $\epsilon _{X}\equiv \log(N_{X}/N_{H})+12.00$ for number density N ; $\epsilon _{H}=12.00$ on this scale.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Another scale is mass fraction or, equivalently, percent by mass.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For example, the abundance of oxygen in pure water can be measured in two ways: the *mass fraction* is about 89%, because that is the fraction of water's mass which is oxygen.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, the *mole fraction* is about 33% because only 1 atom of 3 in water, H2O, is oxygen.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Changing the given environment to Jupiter's outer atmosphere, where hydrogen is diatomic while helium is not, changes the *molecular* mole fraction (fraction of total gas molecules), as well as the fraction of atmosphere by volume, of hydrogen to about 86%, and of helium to 13%.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below Jupiter's outer atmosphere, volume fractions are significantly different from mole fractions due to high temperatures (ionization and disproportionation) and high density, where the ideal gas law is inapplicable.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Remaining elements, making up only about 2% of the universe, were largely produced by supernovae and certain red giant stars.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Lithium, beryllium, and boron, despite their low atomic number, are rare because, although they are produced by nuclear fusion, they are destroyed by other reactions in the stars.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Their natural occurrence is the result of cosmic ray spallation of carbon, nitrogen and oxygen in a type of nuclear fission reaction.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements from carbon to iron are relatively more abundant in the universe because of the ease of making them in supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements of higher atomic numbers than iron (element 26) become progressively rarer in the universe, because they increasingly absorb stellar energy in their production.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Also, elements with even atomic numbers are generally more common than their neighbors in the periodic table, due to favorable energetics of formation (see Oddo–Harkins rule), and among the lightest nuclides helium through sulfur the most abundant isotopes of equal number of protons and neutrons.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is the most abundant element in the Universe; helium is second.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] All others are orders of magnitude less common.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] After this, the rank of abundance does not continue to correspond to the atomic number.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen has abundance rank 3, but atomic number 8.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are 80 known stable elements, and the lightest 16 comprise 99.9% of the ordinary matter of the universe.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Segrè plot is initially linear because (aside from hydrogen) the vast majority of ordinary matter (99.4% in the Solar System) contains an equal number of protons and neutrons (Z=N).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The abundance of the elements up to lithium is well predicted by the standard cosmological model, since they were mostly produced shortly (i.e., within a few hundred seconds) after the Big Bang, in a process known as Big Bang nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements were mostly produced much later, in stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In general, elements up to iron are made by large stars in the process of becoming supernovae, or by smaller stars in the process of dying.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Iron-56 is particularly common, since it is the most stable nuclide (in that it has the highest nuclear binding energy per nucleon) and can easily be "built up" from alpha particles (being a product of decay of radioactive nickel-56, ultimately made from 14 helium nuclei).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Elements heavier than iron are made in energy-absorbing processes in large stars, and their abundance in the universe (and on Earth) generally decreases with increasing atomic number.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The table shows the ten most common elements in our galaxy (estimated spectroscopically), as measured in parts per million, by mass.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Nearby galaxies that have evolved along similar lines have a corresponding enrichment of elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more distant galaxies are being viewed as they appeared in the past, so their abundances of elements appear closer to the primordial mixture.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Since physical laws and processes are apparently uniform throughout the universe, however, it is expected that these galaxies will likewise have evolved similar abundances of elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] As shown in the periodic table, the abundance of elements is in keeping with their origin.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Very abundant hydrogen and helium are products of the Big Bang.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next three elements in the periodic table (lithium, beryllium, and boron) are rare, despite their low atomic number.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They had little time to form in the Big Bang.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] They are produced in small quantities by nuclear fusion in dying stars or by breakup of heavier elements in interstellar dust, caused by cosmic ray spallation.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In supernova stars, they are produced by nuclear fusion, but then destroyed by other reactions.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Heavier elements, beginning with carbon, have been produced in dying or supernova stars by buildup from alpha particles (helium nuclei), contributing to an alternatingly larger abundance of elements with even atomic numbers (these are also more stable).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The effect of odd-numbered chemical elements generally being more rare in the universe was empirically noticed in 1914, and is known as the Oddo–Harkins rule.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The following graph (log scale) shows abundance of elements in the Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Loose correlations have been observed between estimated elemental abundances in the universe and the nuclear binding energy curve (also called the *binding energy per nucleon*).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Roughly speaking, the relative stability of various atomic nuclides in withstanding the extremely energetic conditions of Big Bang nucleosynthesis (BBN) has exerted a strong influence on the relative abundance of elements formed in the Big Bang, and during the development of the universe thereafter.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] See the article about nucleosynthesis for an explanation of how certain nuclear fusion processes in stars (such as carbon burning, etc.) create the elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A similar alternation between even and odd atomic numbers can be observed in the nuclear binding energy curve in the neighborhood of carbon and oxygen, but here the loose correlation between relative abundance and binding energy ends.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The binding energy for beryllium (an even atomic number), for example, is *less* than the binding energy for boron (an odd atomic number), as illustrated in the nuclear binding energy curve.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Additionally, the alternation in the nuclear binding energy between even and odd atomic numbers resolves above oxygen as the graph increases steadily up to its peak at iron.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The semi-empirical mass formula (SEMF), also called *Weizsäcker's formula* or the *Bethe-Weizsäcker mass formula*, gives a theoretical explanation of the overall shape of the curve of nuclear binding energy.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Modern astronomy relies on understanding the abundance of elements in the Sun as part of cosmological models.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Abundance values are difficult to obtain: even photospheric or observational abundances depend upon models of solar atmospherics and radiation coupling.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These astronomical abundance values are reported as logarithms of the ratio with hydrogen.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Hydrogen is set to an abundance of 12 on this scale.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Sun's photosphere consists mostly of hydrogen and helium; the helium abundance varies between about 10.3 and 10.5 depending on the phase of the solar cycle; carbon is 8.47, neon is 8.29, oxygen is 7.69 and iron is estimated at 7.62.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth formed from the same cloud of matter that formed the Sun, but the planets acquired different compositions during the formation and evolution of the Solar System.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In turn, the history of Earth led to parts of the planet having differing concentrations of the elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass of the Earth is approximately 5.97×1024 kg.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, it is composed mostly of iron (32.1%), oxygen (30.1%), silicon (15.1%), magnesium (13.9%), sulfur (2.9%), nickel (1.8%), calcium (1.5%), and aluminium (1.4%); with the remaining 1.2% consisting of trace amounts of other elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The amount of oxygen, silicon, sulfur, carbon, and hydrogen in the Earth's core can only be inferred from theoretical models and consequently the abundance of these elements in the total Earth is not known precisely.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The remaining elemental composition is roughly typical of the "rocky" inner planets, which formed "inside" the "frost line" close to the Sun, where the young Sun's heat and stellar wind drove off volatile compounds into space.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The Earth retains oxygen as the second-largest component of its mass (and largest atomic fraction), mainly due to oxygen's high reactivity; this caused it to bond into silicate minerals which have a high melting point and low vapor pressure.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the nine most abundant elements in the Earth's crust is roughly: oxygen 46%, silicon 28%, aluminium 8.3%, iron 5.6%, calcium 4.2%, sodium 2.5%, magnesium 2.4%, potassium 2.0%, and titanium 0.61%.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other elements occur at less than 0.15%.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] For a full list, see abundance of elements in Earth's crust.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The graph at right illustrates the relative atomic-abundance of the chemical elements in Earth's upper continental crust—the part that is relatively accessible for measurements and estimation.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] 5. the nine rarest "metals" – the six platinum group elements plus Au, Re, and Te (a metalloid) – in the yellow field.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are rare in the crust from being soluble in iron and thus concentrated in Earth's core.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Tellurium is the single most depleted element in the silicate Earth relative to cosmic abundance, because in addition to being concentrated as dense chalcogenides in the core it was severely depleted by preaccretional sorting in the nebula as volatile hydrogen telluride.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are two breaks where the unstable elements technetium (atomic number 43) and promethium (number 61) would be.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These elements are surrounded by stable elements, yet their most stable isotopes have relatively short half-lives (~4 million years and ~18 years respectively).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These are thus extremely rare, since any primordial amounts of these elements have long since decayed.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] These two elements are now only produced naturally through spontaneous fission of very heavy radioactive elements (such as uranium, thorium, or the trace amounts of plutonium that exist in uranium ores), or by the interaction of certain other elements with cosmic rays.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Both technetium and promethium have been identified spectroscopically in the atmospheres of stars, where they are produced by ongoing nucleosynthetic processes.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] There are also breaks in the abundance graph where the six noble gases would be, since they are not chemically bound in the Earth's crust, and so their crustal abundance is not well-defined.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen and silicon are the most common elements in the crust.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] On Earth and rocky planets in general, silicon and oxygen are far more common than their cosmic abundance.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The reason is that they combine with each other to form silicate minerals.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Other cosmically common elements such as hydrogen, carbon and nitrogen form volatile compounds such as ammonia and methane that easily boil away into space from the heat of planetary formation and/or the Sun's light.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] "Rare" earth elements is a historical misnomer.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The persistence of the term reflects unfamiliarity rather than true rarity.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The more abundant rare earth elements are similarly concentrated in the crust compared to commonplace industrial metals such as chromium, nickel, copper, zinc, molybdenum, tin, tungsten, or lead.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The two least abundant stable rare earth elements (thulium and lutetium) are nearly 200 times more common than gold.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] However, in contrast to the ordinary base and precious metals, rare earth elements have very little tendency to become concentrated in exploitable ore deposits.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Consequently, most of the world's supply of rare earth elements comes from only a handful of sources.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Furthermore, the rare earth metals are all quite chemically similar to each other, and they are thus quite difficult to separate into quantities of the pure elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Differences in abundances of individual rare earth elements in the upper continental crust of the Earth represent the superposition of two effects, one nuclear and one geochemical.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] First, the rare earth elements with even atomic numbers (58Ce, 60Nd, ...) have greater cosmic and terrestrial abundances than the adjacent rare earth elements with odd atomic numbers (57La, 59Pr, ...).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Second, the lighter rare earth elements are more incompatible (because they have larger ionic radii) and therefore more strongly concentrated in the continental crust than the heavier rare earth elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] In most rare earth ore deposits, the first four rare earth elements – lanthanum, cerium, praseodymium, and neodymium – constitute 80% to 99% of the total amount of rare earth metal that can be found in the ore.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The mass-abundance of the seven most abundant elements in the Earth's mantle is approximately: oxygen 44.3%, magnesium 22.3%, silicon 21.3%, iron 6.32%, calcium 2.48%, aluminium 2.29%, nickel 0.19%.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Due to mass segregation, the core of the Earth is believed to be primarily composed of iron (88.8%), with smaller amounts of nickel (5.8%), sulfur (4.5%), and less than 1% trace elements.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Sulfur, phosphorus, and all other elements are present in significantly lower proportions.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] According to the abundance curve graph, argon, a significant if not major component of the atmosphere, does not appear in the crust at all.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] This is because the atmosphere has a far smaller mass than the crust, so argon remaining in the crust contributes little to mass fraction there, while at the same time buildup of argon in the atmosphere has become large enough to be significant.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] By mass, human cells consist of 65–90% water (H2O), and a significant portion of the remainder is composed of carbon-containing organic molecules.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Oxygen therefore contributes a majority of a human body's mass, followed by carbon.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Almost 99% of the mass of the human body is made up of six elements: hydrogen (H), carbon (C), nitrogen (N), oxygen (O), calcium (Ca), and phosphorus (P).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The next 0.75% is made up of the next five elements: potassium (K), sulfur (S), chlorine (Cl), sodium (Na), and magnesium (Mg).
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Only 17 elements are known for certain to be necessary to human life, with one additional element (fluorine) thought to be helpful for tooth enamel strength.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] A few more trace elements may play some role in the health of mammals.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Boron and silicon are notably necessary for plants but have uncertain roles in animals.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] The elements aluminium and silicon, although very common in the earth's crust, are conspicuously rare in the human body.
[src:abiogenesis/abundance-of-the-chemical-elements] Below is a periodic table highlighting nutritional elements.
[src:abiogenesis/academic-press] Academic Press publishes books and reference materials in fields including communications engineering, economics, environmental science, finance, food science, geophysics, life sciences, mathematics, neuroscience, psychology, and the physical sciences.
[src:abiogenesis/acs-central-science] Established in 2015, it is the first fully open-access journal (diamond open access) published by ACS Publications, the American Chemical Society's publishing arm.
[src:abiogenesis/acs-central-science] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 12.7.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:abiogenesis/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
